      <title>The topology of decision games</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/the-topology-of-decision-games/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 14 Jan 2025 12:33:23 -0300</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/the-topology-of-decision-games/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;tldr&#34;&gt;TL;DR&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Bla&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xD;&#xA;    &lt;aside id=&#34;TableOfContents&#34;&gt;&#xD;&#xA;        &lt;nav id=&#34;TableOfContents&#34;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;ol&gt;&#xA;    &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#tldr&#34;&gt;TL;DR&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;    &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#simplices-probabilities-and-decision-games&#34;&gt;Simplices, probabilities and decision games&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;    &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#nash-equilibria&#34;&gt;Nash equilibria&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;    &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#2x2-games-and-their-topology&#34;&gt;2x2 games and their topology&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/ol&gt;&#xA;&lt;/nav&gt;&#xD;&#xA;    &lt;/aside&gt;&#xD;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;simplices-probabilities-and-decision-games&#34;&gt;Simplices, probabilities and decision games&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;PROB&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The fact that the standard simplex $\Delta^n$ can be simply described as $\{(\lambda_1,...,\lambda_n)\mid  \sum_{i=1}^n \lambda_i=1, \,\lambda_i\geq 0\}$ make it so that points $p\in \Delta^n$ can be intepreted as &lt;strong&gt;probabilities&lt;/strong&gt; associated to $n$ possible events&amp;ndash; with each $\lambda_i$ of $p$ being the probability of the $i$-th event to occur. This opens up a bridge between topology and probability, that has been particularly useful in one area of mathematics: &lt;strong&gt;game theory&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
